Yes, that mapping is clean and minimal.

## Proposed fix

In `packages/ai/src/providers/openai-completions.ts`, normalize `reasoning_effort` right before assigning it to params.

### Mapping rule for Groq

- `"none"` -> `"none"`
- any other pi-ai effort (`minimal|low|medium|high|xhigh`) -> `"default"`

### For all other providers

- keep existing behavior

---

### Suggested code shape

1. Update type:

```ts
reasoningEffort?: "none" | "minimal" | "low" | "medium" | "high" | "xhigh";
```

2. Add helper in same file:

```ts
function normalizeReasoningEffort(
  model: Model<"openai-completions">,
  effort: OpenAICompletionsOptions["reasoningEffort"] | undefined,
): OpenAICompletionsOptions["reasoningEffort"] | "default" | undefined {
  if (!effort) return undefined;

  const isGroq = model.provider === "groq" || model.baseUrl.includes("groq.com");
  if (!isGroq) return effort;

  return effort === "none" ? "none" : "default";
}
```

3. Use it in `buildParams()`:

```ts
const normalizedEffort = normalizeReasoningEffort(model, options?.reasoningEffort);
if (normalizedEffort && model.reasoning && compat.supportsReasoningEffort) {
  params.reasoning_effort = normalizedEffort;
}
```

## Why this is nice

- Single-point normalization.
- Provider-specific behavior stays local to `openai-completions`.
- No behavior change for non-Groq providers.
- Supports explicit `"none"` for callers using provider-level options.

## Tests to add

- `streamSimple(... reasoning: "medium")` on Groq model -> payload contains `reasoning_effort: "default"`.
- `stream(... reasoningEffort: "none")` on Groq model -> payload contains `reasoning_effort: "none"`.
- Non-Groq model with `"medium"` -> payload remains `"medium"`.

If you want, I can implement this patch and add the tests now.

